rgues that civilisations are best understood as the products of routine contacts and connections carried out by anonymous actors over the course of long periods of time. It illustrates this argument through case studies of modern Japan, the Pacific and post-Conquest Latin America (including the revival of indigenous civilisations), exploring discourses of civilisation outside the West within the context of growing Western imperial power.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCivilizationxPhilosophy. 0aComparative civilization. 0aCultural pluralism. 0aIntercultural communication. 0aPolitical science (General). 0aSociology (General). 4aPolitical Studies 2019. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / Diplomacy.2bisacsh  aEurope.  aGeorge Pachymeres.  aIbn Khaldun.  aJapan.  aLatin America.  aPacific cultures.  aSimon Bolivar.  acapitalism.  acollective memory.  acolonialism.  acontemporary civilisational analysis.  aearly modernities.  ahuman imaginaries.  ainter-civilisational engagement.  ainter-cultural encounters.  ainter-societal encounters.  aislander experiences.  aoceanian civilisation.  apolitical economy.  apost-Cold War period.1 aSmith, Jeremy C.A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2017 eBook-Packagez978311128281740uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/9781526105318zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526105318zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526105318/original  a978-3-11-128281-7 Manchester University Press 2017 eBook-Packageb2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA